1. PATCH() Function:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ The PATCH() Function is used to create a record, update a record in a data source.
âœ… Syntax: Patch(DataSource, Defaults(DataSource), { Column1: Value1, Column2: Value2, Column3: Value3 })
ðŸ’› Syntax: Patch(Employees, Defaults(Employees), { Name: "Manoj", Age: 25, Department: "IT" })

ðŸ‘‰ If I want to update only specific fields of a record without affecting other data, Patch() is the best choice.
âœ… For example: If you want to update a specific employee whose name is "John Doe":-
ðŸ’› Syntax: Patch(Employees, LookUp(Employees, Name = "Manoj"),{Age: 20, Department: "HR"})
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2. LOOKUP() Function:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ The LookUp() function is used to retrieve single record from a data source that matches a specific condition.
ðŸ’› Syntax: LookUp(DataSource, Condition [column])

âœ… For example: Find the Name field only from the employee record.
âž¡ï¸ LookUp(Employees, Name:"Manoj") 
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

3. FILTER() Function:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ The Filter() function is used to retrieve multiple records from a data source that matches a specific condition.
ðŸ’› Syntax: Filter(DataSource, Condition)

âœ… For Example: Get all employees who work in the IT department.
âž¡ï¸ Filter(Employees, Department = "IT") ---> This returns all records where the Department field is "IT".
âž¡ï¸ Filter(Employees, Department =Dropdown.Selected.Value) ---> Users selects the dropdown and returns that specific criteria.
âž¡ï¸ If(Dropdown.Selected.Value= "All",Employess, Filter(Employees, Department=Dropdown.Selected.Value)) ---> Users selects all & returns all data.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

4. SEARCH() Function:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ The Search() function is used to search for text within a specific column of a data source and returns all matching records.
ðŸ‘‰ It is a "Case-Insensitive", it doesn't matter whether the text searching for upper or lower case.
ðŸ’› Syntax: Search(DataSource, SearchString, ColumnName)

âœ… For Example: To search for employees whose Name contains the text "John".
âž¡ï¸ Search(Employees, "John", "Name") ---> This returns all records where the Name column contains the word "John"/"JOHN".
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

5. SORT() Function:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ The Sort() function is used to sort records in a data source based on a specific column or field.
ðŸ‘‰ We can sort the data in either ascending or descending order.
ðŸ’› Syntax: Sort(DataSource, ColumnName, SortOrder)

âœ… Example: Sort employees by their Age in ascending order (youngest to oldest):
âž¡ï¸ Sort(Employees, Age, Ascending) --->  This sorts the Employees list so that employees with the smallest age appear first.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

6. IsMatch() Function:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ The IsMatch() function is used to check if a text string matches a specific pattern, usually defined by a regular expression (RegEx).
ðŸ‘‰ It returns true or false, making it useful for validating user inputs like: Email addresses, Phone numbers, PIN codes, Password formats.
ðŸ’› Syntax: IsMatch(EmailInput.Text, pattern) 
âœ… Example:
In a login form, I used IsMatch() Function to check if the email input matched the correct pattern before allowing submission.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

7. Match() Function:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ The Match() function is used to find and return the first match of a pattern within a text string. (regular expression)
ðŸ‘‰ It is similar to IsMatch(), which returns true/false, Match() returns the actual matched value found in the text.
âœ… Example:
If I have a log message or input string, and I want to extract the first number, email, or keyword, I use Match().
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

8. MatchAll() Function:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ The MatchAll() function is used to find all occurrences of a pattern within a text string.
ðŸ‘‰ It returns a table of all matched values, not just the first one.
âœ… Example:
If I need to extract all email addresses or all numbers from a long message, I use MatchAll(), It returns all matches as a table.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

9. Switch() Function:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ The Switch function is used to check one condition or one expression against multiple values.
ðŸ‘‰ Itâ€™s cleaner and more readable than writing multiple If() statements when comparing the same variable, 
   â€” for example, checking different user roles or change the label color based on condition.
ðŸ’› Syntax: Switch(expression, value1, result1, value2, result2, ..., default)

âœ… Example Use Cases:
ðŸ”¹ If the User selects "Manager", it will return "Welcome Manager!".
ðŸ‘‰ Fill Property: Switch(Dropdown1.Selected.Value,"Admin",Color.Red,"Manager",Color.Yellow,"HR")
ðŸ‘‰ Text Property: Switch(Dropdown.Selected.Value, "Admin", "Welcome Admin!", "Manager", "Welcome Manager!")
                      (OR)
ðŸ”¹ Change label or text colour based on the selection Dropdown value.
ðŸ‘‰ Fill: Switch(Dropdown.Selected.Value, "1",Color.Red, "2",Color.Green, "3",Color.Yellow)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

10. If() Function:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ If() function is used for multiple logical conditions like ranges or combined expressions using operators like (>, <, =, And, Or).
ðŸ‘‰ Itâ€™s more flexible when you need to evaluate different types of conditions, not just one variable.
ðŸ’› Syntax: If(condition, result, [condition2, result2, ..., default])

âœ… Example Use Cases:
ðŸ”¹ Change label or text colour based on the selection list box.
ðŸ‘‰ Fill Property: If(Listbox.Selected.Value = "1",Color.Red,
                  If(Listbox.Selected.Value = "2",Color.Green,
                  If(Listbox.Selected.Value = "3",Color.Yellow)))

ðŸ‘‰ Text Property: If(Listbox.Selected.Value = "1","Welcome to 1",
                  If(Listbox.Selected.Value = "2","Welcome to 2"
                  If(Listbox.Selected.Value = "3","Welcome to 3")))
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

11. Differnce between ComboBox AND DropDown Controls?
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
âœ… DropDown Control: 
ðŸ‘‰ DropDown control lets users select a single value from a list of predefined options.
ðŸ‘‰ Itâ€™s simple and ideal when the choices are few and selection is limited to one.

âœ… ComboBox Control:
ðŸ‘‰ ComboBox control allows users to select single or multiple values, and also supports searching/filtering through the options.
ðŸ‘‰ It is more flexible and interactive than a DropDown.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

12. SharePoint in Power Apps:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ SharePoint is a Microsoft web-based collaboration platform.
ðŸ‘‰ I use SharePoint as a common data source in Power Apps for storing and managing lists and documents.
ðŸ‘‰ It acts as a centralized backend for managing documents, lists, and other data, and integrates easily with Power Apps.
ðŸ‘‰ Using SharePoint helps deliver quick solutions without complex backend setups.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âœ… SharePoint Team Site:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ Used for: Team work and collaboration
ðŸ‘‰ Who uses it: Small team (like a project team, department)
What you can do:
ðŸ‘‰ Everyone can edit, upload files, and work together
ðŸ‘‰ Integrated with Microsoft Teams, Outlook, Planner
Example:
ðŸ‘‰ You and your project team are building a product. You need to share files, assign tasks, track progress â€” use a Team Site.

ðŸ“¢ SharePoint Communication Site:
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
